A:

Instead of 
rs.getDate(3)

you should use 
rs.getString(3)

because the data is already formatted as String. If you want to get as Date, first, a Date object is created from your 05-11-2013 string, then you receive that. If you have Date objects in your objects, you should either parse() the returnes string with the same format you returned from the DB, or let the JDBC do the conversion for you (in this case, simply select idabbonamento, tipo, datainizio, ...) without formatting. I recommend that let JDBC do it. Less user code, less trouble :)
String queryAbb = "select idabbonamento, tipo, datainizio, datascadenza, ...";
...
a.setDataInizio(rs.getDate(3));
// reading the formatted data:
System.out.println(new SimpleDateFormat().format(a.getDataInizio());

Actually, there is one more trick, but you don't have to care about: rs.getDate() returns java.sql.Date, but you probably use java.util.Date.

